Sans who were “in manu patris” could legally possess no property oi their own, though they were often allowed to hold aparctiam, just as the slaves were. See note on Sat. iii. 189. They could therefore not dispose of any property by will as long as their father was alive. After the time ο Augustus, however, this rule was relaxed in the case os soldiers, who were allowed to treat all property acquired by their military services ( “ castrense peculium quae sunt parta labore militiae '') as their own, and accordingly to dispose of it by will.
